# LunarSystem — outbound links (the "stop being an island" file).
#
# Operator-curated statements that connect THIS site's resources to the wider web of
# data. Without them the graph is well-formed RDF that links to nothing; with them a
# consumer — or an agent — can follow its nose from a LunarSystem page out to an
# external entity, and external datasets can point back in via owl:sameAs.
#
# Subjects are RELATIVE /id/ IRIs — <root>, <journal>, … — i.e. a content slug. They
# resolve against the live {site}/id/ base when projected, so this file is
# deployment-independent: the same statements work on localhost and in production.
#
# Each statement is merged into every published representation of its resource:
# ?output=turtle/xml/json, the embedded + ?output=jsonld JSON-LD, the dereferenceable
# /data/{slug} document, and — after `make resync-triplestore` — the triplestore, so
# SPARQL sees them too. A missing or empty file is a silent no-op.
#
# Curate honestly. owl:sameAs / schema:sameAs assert IDENTITY (the object *is* this
# thing — its Wikidata/ORCID/official URL); rdfs:seeAlso / schema:about are the weaker
# "related to" / "is about". Patterns to copy:
#
#   <a-concept-page>  owl:sameAs    <https://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q42> .
#   <a-person-page>   schema:sameAs <https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1825-0097> .

@prefix owl:    <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdfs:   <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix schema: <https://schema.org/> .

# The home page's canonical reference is the project repository; the welcome article
# is about the project. (Seed examples — replace with your own.)
<root>
    schema:sameAs <https://github.com/jeromev/LunarSystem> ;
    rdfs:seeAlso  <https://github.com/jeromev/LunarSystem> .

<welcome>
    schema:about <https://github.com/jeromev/LunarSystem> .
